title: The Wisconsin Community
text: When I think of my community, all of Wisconsin comes to mind.  I've traveled to many parts of the state and feel connected to all of them.  Let's make a map which embodies the ideas that unite Wisconsinites--political fairness, competitiveness, compactness, equal population, contiguity, and the Voting Rights Act--not those which divide us.  If smaller communities of interest (COIs) are formed, who gets to decide which COIs are "worthy" and which are not?  The most important community of interest is the entire state.

title: Moraine Park Technical College
text: This community of interest focuses on the main campus of the Moraine Park Technical College district, in Fond du lac.
area_text: The main college is located in Fond du lac, WI adjacent to the University of Wisconsin- Fond du lac. There are also two other campuses located in Beaver Dam and West Bend. Currently the Moraine Park Technical College district spans coverage over 308,000 Wisconsin residents.

title: Nicolet Area Technical College (NATC)
text: This community of interest focuses in on the main campus of the NATC region, in Rhinelander.
area_text: NATC is located in northern Wisconsin specifically in Rhinelander. It's district provides coverage for over 92,000 residents. Their district spans over 4,000 sq. miles across the region and they have campuses in outreach centers in Carter, Crandon, Eagle River, the Forest County Potawatomi Community, Lac du Flambeau, Minocqua, Mole Lake, and Tomahawk.  It is clear NATC is crucial to rural Wisconsin residents as their options are typically limited due to their geographical location.

title: Forest County Area - Call for Peace
text: Forest County Area:    I return regularly to my Potawatomi relatives in Forest County for our universal language of dance, traditional drumming, and wise teachings of peace.  Colonization and white supremacy has subjected Potawatomi and Ojibwe to broken treaties and deadly treatment. For example, see https://glifwc.org/publications/pdf/SandyLake_Brochure.pdf .  On top of that, in the 1980’s a zinc and copper mine plan was set to destroy Rice Lake and pollute the watershed. It was the Sokaogon Band of Lake Superior Ojibwe and the Forest County Potawatomi who, in 2003, prevented this disaster for all of WI.  They purchased the Crandon Mine site. They had formed alliances with their non-native neighbors and with a multitude of tribes and environmentalists. They teach us that together we can bring peace and justice to desperate situations. We owe all indigenous in Wisconsin fair maps and proper voting rights, on top of just resolution of long standing land, ceded land, and water pollution issues.    As co-founder of Call for Peace Drum & Dance Company, I pledge to continue my call for peace founded on justice… reflecting on the ways of my Forest County area relatives.

title: Central Sands Region
text: THe Central Sands region is a rural community rich in natural resources.  Numerous lakes and rivers, forests and wetlands are found in this community.  Large agribusinesses are vying for its resources and changing the water quality. Hunoing, fishing, and water activities  make tourism an important aspect of the economy. Its rural nature results in needs in the areas of healthcare, housing, and transportation.
area_text:
This community is a rural area in central Wisconsin that is primarily, lakes, rivers, wetlands, woods, and farmland. Its location is east of the Wisconsin  River.   The Ice Age Trail meanders through it.  Hunting and fishing are important activities.  
Agribusinesses use over 3,000 high capacity wells in this region.  

Stevens Point is that largest city in the region.  Many small towns are located within this region.  It's rural nature creates unique needs in the areas of healthhcare, housing, and transportation.
The Central Sands Water Action Coalition is a group of non-profit organizations dedicated to protecting lakes, rivers and wetlands by advancing sustainable groundwater policies in the Central Sands Region of Wisconsin.

title: Iowa County - Postcard
text: The postcard group has been meeting for over 4 years.  It's an opportunity to contact legislators and other leaders regarding issues that concern us and offer thanks for actions taken and leadership.  We learn from one another and we have formed a community.  Currently, Iowa County is split into 3 districts and we believe it is important to have representation that attends to our rural concerns.
area_text: Counties are a unit of government with their own County Board of Supervisors.  In small counties, such as Iowa County, there is often one resource for things like police, healthcare, business development, etc.  The postcard group has been meeting weekly for over 4 years and is comprised of people from throughout the county.  To be kept intact for our legislative representatives will provide us with a stronger voice in advocating for rural issues such as environmental issues, rural healthcare, rural broadband, rural public education.

title: Menominee County + 2 townships
text: My Community of Interest is seen when connecting Menominee County to two adjoining Towns of Red Springs and Bartelme. Together we form one rectangle and accompany part of  the Wolf River. This reunites those of us working for the same values and interests into this compact, contiguous rectangle that does not break municipal or county lines.  The 6,293 residents are 65.9% indigenous,  5.1% of two races,  and 5.1% Hispanic. We all depend on clean water and the Wolf River.

title: Jen's Northside Madison Map
text: Northside of Madison map.
area_text:
Diverse and little known area of Madison. Mix of residential/industry/services. There are gaps in those areas for people who live there. 

Range of high income, low income, middle income. Mix of high income housing and affordable housing. 

Community values mom/pop stores and doesn't want large chains/gentrification.

Service industry and government work (county/city) are significant employers.

Significant retired community and young families. 

School system serves lower socio-economic students. Teachers/staff are dedicated to those schools. 

Lots of natural areas in the community that people really treasure. 

Issues/Concerns:
Safety--fear of the police and policing, but a desire for public safety (particularly around public housing areas).
Water quality--there is a of severely compromised water in the parks/lakes/marshes.  People can't recreate. 
Business Development--Businesses are being pushed/priced/taxed out of the area. Lots of gentrification (which is not the character of the Northside). 
Airport--Deafening noise from military helicopters/planes/fighter jets. Unsuccessful campaign to stop F-35. 
Transportation--not adequate bus routes to service the entire community with direct routes to where people need to go. 
High speed drivers--lots of speedy and accidents. 
Higher quality schools--people have a desire for this. More financial resources are need and lower teacher/student ratio. 
Affordable Housing--people that have service jobs are being priced out of rent and homeownership.

text: The map of this community represents Northeast Wisconsin Technical College, a public college that serves the Green Bay area. It serves roughly 41,500 people a year, and the campus must be kept together as a single community. That school offers over 100 associate degrees, technical diplomas, 84 certificates, and apprenticeships. The school also serves 1,084 business through a corporate training department. title: Oneida Nation of Wisconsin
text: Oneida Nation of Wisconsin Reservation
area_text: The Oneida Nation of Wisconsin is a sovereign First Nation. It's reservation has been checkerboarded, meaning many pieces of land are not owned by the Oneida Nation causing maps of owned land to look similar to a checkerboard. This is due to the Dawes Act of 1887 which sought to take reservation land from First Nations and force assimilation. Oneida has been buying back land but only owns about 65% of the land within it's reservation boundaries. The community shares cultural values and common goals. Community members enjoy lacrosse, Oneida's annual Pow Wow, cultural events, and hunting and fishing.

title: Two distinct communities, united as one
text: I live in the Town of Beloit, just north of the City of Beloit.  At one time, our area was probably a sundown town, meaning Blacks would have to leave by sundown or they would face dire consequences. By including Janesville and Beloit in the same district can help to balance the ethnic influence in elections.  Beloit also has a greater Hispanic population.  This also is a reason to include both communities in the same election map.

title: Iowa County functions as One Community
text: My community of interest is the entirety of Iowa County. Our geology connects us as a community. We are deeply connected by the way we care for this land and for each other.  Bordered on the North by the Wisconsin River, Iowa County’s Driftless Area river valleys, towering rock outcrops and rolling hills foster special care and local pride. Several of our many cold water streams boast Class 1 trout fishing. They include four DNR Creek Fisheries being studied as Exceptional Water Resources. Our county has seven State Natural Areas adding up to almost 4,000 acres of bio-diverse land that give us a glimpse into what our lands were like 200 years ago.  But can we preserve our amazing ecology? Continuing together, yes! There is a long tradition here of preventing erosion on our hillsides by strip farming. And family farmers here seem to lead the state in no-till and cover crop techniques. We hold farmers in our hearts during these difficult times.  Recent studies have shown high levels of nitrates in some private wells. Our Karst terrain can be exacerbating this problem with its shallow soil, fissures, cracks and caves. There is high potential for surface water runoff to bypass natural soil filtration bringing contaminants into drinking water.  Adding more deep intrusions into this terrain could increase water contamination. Two kinds of major intrusions are being proposed in Iowa County. And we, countywide, would pay the price. 1) After extensive citizen objections, our Iowa County Board registered its opposition to ATC utilities creating a new high-voltage transmission line that would disrupt our fragile land. Even Public Service Commission (PSC) staff and many conservation groups had recommended local renewable power which would avoid damaging natural areas. Iowa County joined many ratepayers to appeal the PSC decision. Conflicts of interest by some PSC members are part of appeals, which are still pending. 2) A multinational is taking advantage of WI’s lax corporate regulations and approaching individual landowners to sign leases to spread 172 utility scale wind turbines around Cobb, Linden, Mineral Point, Dodgeville, Mifflin, Waldwick, Eden, Highland and Moscow. Foundations for these 650’ tall turbines would be set deep into the unstable Karst terrain. This “Uplands” wind project is dependent on the proposed ATC transmission line still in the appeals process. After meeting with residents in opposition, Iowa County legislators have called on Governor Evers to hold a hearing on the subject.  Many of us engage in hands on conservation work. We volunteer in groups like Friends of the Ridgeway State Natural Area, Friends of the Military Ridge State Trail, the Driftless Area Land Conservancy, Bethel Horizons Camp, Prairie Enthusiasts, Kiwanis’ Clean Boats/Clean Lakes and more.  Iowa County has a long history of economic interdependence. From ancient times Native peoples mined lead found close to the ground surface. In fact Iowa County is thought to be named after a Native Tribe who mined lead from what became the Mineral Point area. Early lead and then also zinc mining brought emigrants from Cornwall, England, from Wales and from Norway to Mineral Point and eventually to Dodgeville. Mining stopped decades ago, but traditions of carrying Cornish pasties continues in many fundraisers. Many hundreds of mining sites are recorded. Due to the makeup of our land, quarrying for stone foundations and for road surfaces is longstanding and still serves a wide area. The Iowa County courthouse, the oldest, active courthouse in the state of Wisconsin, was built of native limestone by skilled Cornish masons. It is one of many handsome buildings in downtown Dodgeville that date to the 1800s.  Family farming, flour mills, cheese factories, taverns and apple orchards sprang up easily. We still enjoy these and crafts such as carpentry, architecture, fiber arts, pottery, painting, making music and drama. We also gather for biking, hiking, music, dance, arts.  We have a common ethic of helping each other out. All eleven Fire Departments of Iowa County are volunteer and they work with each other. We support a joint volunteer Iowa County Technical Rescue Team to assist local EMTs, police and fire departments in more difficult rescues.  Iowa County has eight public libraries who work together for library access for all residents. Their outreach includes many additional Pop-up libraries.  The Dodgeville Public Library is currently training volunteers to provide hours of library service within the Ridgeway Community Center. The Dodgeville Chronicle and The Democrat Tribune newspapers help us hear from each other.  Upland Hills Health is our community hospital with a volunteer board of directors representing our local areas. It is a critical access hospital that also has seven family medicine clinic locations and a Nursing and Rehab Center. Other exercise and wellness opportunities are posted with the county. A Meals on Wheels program is active with volunteer support.  Thirty one congregations are listed at https://www.iowacounty.org/religious-institutions. They are active in the community, opening their doors in service. One example is the Wednesday evening Feeding Friends meal. A large number of congregations, PTO's and civic groups take turns bringing the various foods for the particular menu and sit down and eat with those who come for the meal.  Farmers Markets are held on Saturdays in Dodgeville, Saturdays in Mineral Point and Sundays in Ridgeway. We cherish our grocery stores and their cheese and meat counters in Dodgeville, Mineral Point and Hollandale. The Uplands Garden Club meets in Dodgeville and on sites of member gradens. There is a new Garden and Nature Club in Ridgeway. Besides, native plants at the village signs, this club is doing amazing, innovative work of enhancing native species around a fairly new retention pond. This helps habitat for beneficial wildlife. Permanent benches are placed for contemplation.  The historic venues that we visit and show visitors include Taliesin, House on the Rock, Hyde’s Mill, Folklore Village folk art, American Players Theater, Shake Rag Alley art education center, Pendarvis Historic Site, Botham Vineyards & Winery, Spurgeon Vineyards & Winery, Nick Engelbert’s Grandview, the White Church Theatre Project and the Mineral Point Opera House, among others.  Finally, we understand that even as a county, we are not an island onto ourselves. Many of us communicate through broader groups like the WI League of Municipalities, UW Extension, the Regional Plan Commission, the Fair Maps Coalition and Wisconsin Network for Peace and Justice.  You can see my video on advocacy for Restoring Fair Taxes and Increasing State Aid to local governments at https://youtu.be/wWJB-jwZW-Y.  You will notice how small rural communities are in pain from the tragic closing of some of their school buildings due to reduced state aid for education. Yes, Iowa County naturally connects us as a community of interest by its geology. And we are deeply connected by the way we care for the earth and for each other.  Rev. Mary Kay Baum, 201 Dougherty Court, Ridgeway, 53582 608-935-5834 marykbaum@gmail.com Member of the Board of Trustees of the Ridgeway Village Chair of the Friends of the Ridgeway Pine Relict State Natural Area

There is a new Garden and Nature Club in Ridgeway. Besides, native plants at the village signs, this club is doing amazing, innovative work of enhancing native species around a fairly new retention pond. This helps habitat for beneficial wildlife. Permanent benches are placed for contemplation. The historic venues that we visit and show visitors include Taliesin, House on the Rock, Hyde’s Mill, Folklore Village folk art, American Players Theater, Shake Rag Alley art education center, Pendarvis Historic Site, Botham Vineyards & Winery, Spurgeon Vineyards & Winery, Nick Engelbert’s Grandview, the White Church Theatre Project and the Mineral Point Opera House, among others. Finally, we understand that even as a county, we are not an island onto ourselves. Many of us communicate through broader groups like the WI League of Municipalities, UW Extension, the Regional Plan Commission, the Fair Maps Coalition and Wisconsin Network for Peace and Justice. You can see my video on advocacy for Restoring Fair Taxes and Increasing State Aid to local governments at https://youtu.be/wWJB-jwZW-Y. You will notice how small rural communities are in pain from the tragic closing of some of their school buildings due to reduced state aid for education. Yes, Iowa County naturally connects us as a community of interest by its geology. And we are deeply connected by the way we care for the earth and for each other. Rev. Mary Kay Baum, 201 Dougherty Court, Ridgeway, 53582 608-935-5834 marykbaum@gmail.com Member of the Board of Trustees of the Ridgeway Village Chair of the Friends of the Ridgeway Pine Relict State Natural Area
area_text:
My community of interest is the entirety of Iowa County. Our geology connects us as a community. We are deeply connected by the way we care for this land and for each other.   
Bordered on the North by the Wisconsin River, Iowa County’s Driftless Area river valleys, towering rock outcrops and rolling hills foster special care and local pride. Several of our many cold water streams boast Class 1 trout fishing. They include four DNR Creek Fisheries being studied as Exceptional Water Resources. Our county has seven State Natural Areas adding up to almost 4,000 acres of bio-diverse land that give us a glimpse into what our lands were like 200 years ago. 
But can we preserve our amazing ecology?  Continuing together, yes!  There is a long tradition here of preventing erosion on our hillsides by strip farming. And family farmers here seem to lead the state in no-till and cover crop techniques. We hold farmers in our hearts during these difficult times.   
Recent studies have shown high levels of nitrates in some private wells. Our Karst terrain can be exacerbating this problem with its shallow soil, fissures, cracks and caves. There is high potential for surface water runoff to bypass natural soil filtration bringing contaminants into drinking water.   
Adding more deep intrusions into this terrain could increase water contamination. Two kinds of major intrusions are being proposed in Iowa County. And we, countywide, would pay the price.  
1) After extensive citizen objections, our Iowa County Board registered its opposition to ATC utilities creating a new high-voltage transmission line that would disrupt our fragile land. Even Public Service Commission (PSC) staff and many conservation groups had recommended local renewable power which would avoid damaging natural areas. Iowa County joined many ratepayers to appeal the PSC decision. Conflicts of interest by some PSC members are part of appeals, which are still pending. 
2) A multinational is taking advantage of WI’s lax corporate regulations and approaching individual landowners to sign leases to spread 172 utility scale wind turbines around Cobb, Linden, Mineral Point, Dodgeville, Mifflin, Waldwick, Eden, Highland and Moscow. Foundations for these 650’ tall turbines would be set deep into the unstable Karst terrain. This “Uplands” wind project is dependent on the proposed ATC transmission line still in the appeals process. After meeting with residents in opposition, Iowa County legislators have called on Governor Evers to hold a hearing on the subject. 
Many of us engage in hands on conservation work. We volunteer in groups like Friends of the Ridgeway State Natural Area, Friends of the Military Ridge State Trail,  the Driftless Area Land Conservancy, Bethel Horizons Camp, Prairie Enthusiasts, Kiwanis’ Clean Boats/Clean Lakes and more. 
Iowa County has a long history of economic interdependence. From ancient times Native peoples mined lead found close to the ground surface. In fact Iowa County is thought to be named after a Native Tribe who mined lead from what became the Mineral Point area. Early lead and then also zinc mining brought emigrants from Cornwall, England, from Wales and from Norway to Mineral Point and eventually to Dodgeville.  Mining stopped decades ago, but traditions of carrying Cornish pasties continues in many fundraisers. Many hundreds of mining sites are recorded. 
Due to the makeup of our land, quarrying for stone foundations and for road surfaces is longstanding and still serves a wide area. The Iowa County courthouse, the oldest, active courthouse in the state of Wisconsin, was built of native limestone by skilled Cornish masons. It is one of many handsome buildings in downtown Dodgeville that date to the 1800s. 
Family farming, flour mills, cheese factories, taverns and apple orchards sprang up easily.  We still enjoy these and crafts such as carpentry, architecture, fiber arts, pottery, painting, making music and drama. We also gather for biking, hiking, music, dance, arts.  
We have a common ethic of helping each other out. All eleven Fire Departments of Iowa County are volunteer and they work with each other.   We support a joint volunteer Iowa County Technical Rescue Team to assist local EMTs, police and fire departments in more difficult rescues. 
Iowa County has eight public libraries who work together for library access for all residents.  Their outreach includes many additional Pop-up libraries.  The Dodgeville Public Library is currently training volunteers to provide hours of library service within the Ridgeway Community Center.  The Dodgeville Chronicle and The Democrat Tribune newspapers help us hear from each other. 
Upland Hills Health is our community hospital with a volunteer board of directors representing our local areas. It is a critical access hospital that also has seven family medicine clinic locations and a Nursing and Rehab Center.  Other exercise and wellness opportunities are posted with the county. A Meals on Wheels program is active with volunteer support. 
Thirty one congregations are listed at https://www.iowacounty.org/religious-institutions. They are active in the community, opening their doors in service.  One example is the Wednesday evening Feeding Friends meal. A large number of congregations, PTO's and civic groups take turns bringing the various foods for the particular menu and sit down and eat with those who come for the meal.  
Farmers Markets are held on Saturdays in Dodgeville, Saturdays in Mineral Point and Sundays in Ridgeway.  We cherish our grocery stores and their cheese and meat counters in Dodgeville, Mineral Point and Hollandale. The Uplands Garden Club meets in Dodgeville and on sites of member gardens. There is a new Garden and Nature Club in Ridgeway. Besides, native plants at the village signs, this club is doing amazing, innovative work of enhancing native species around a fairly new retention pond. This helps habitat for beneficial wildlife. Permanent benches are placed for contemplation.
The historic venues that we visit and show visitors include Taliesin, House on the Rock, Hyde’s Mill, Folklore Village folk art, American Players Theater, Shake Rag Alley art education center, Pendarvis Historic Site, Botham Vineyards & Winery, Spurgeon Vineyards & Winery, Nick Engelbert’s Grandview, the White Church Theatre Project and the Mineral Point Opera House, among others.
Finally, we understand that even as a county, we are not an island onto ourselves. Many of us communicate through broader groups like the WI League of Municipalities, UW Extension, the Regional Plan Commission, the Fair Maps Coalition and Wisconsin Network for Peace and Justice. You can see my video on advocacy for Restoring Fair Taxes and Increasing State Aid to local governments at https://youtu.be/wWJB-jwZW-Y.  You will notice how small rural communities are in pain from the tragic closing some of their school buildings due to reduced state aid for education.   
Yes, Iowa County naturally connects us as a community of interest by its geology. And we are deeply connected by the way we care for the earth and  for each other ... Keep us together to clearly hear our voices.
Rev. Mary Kay Baum, 201 Dougherty Court, Ridgeway, 53582  608-935-5834  marykbaum@gmail.com 
Member of the Board of Trustees of the Ridgeway Village 
Chair of the Friends of the Ridgeway Pine Relict State Natural Area

title: Charlotte's 07/29/2021
text: This community is majority Black people. Some important places in this community are The liquor store on 23rd and Capitol hooks fish JJ's Walgreens on Capitol. Some important issues that the local official need to pay more attention to are Parks transportation.

title: WI Needs Fair Maps!
text: We need fair and representative maps in Wisconsin and I commend the effort of all those working hard to make this a reality for our great state. It is no secret that politicians have historically drawn up districts that would divide communities they may see as opposition. Rather than having politicians who will look out for their best interests decide how maps are drawn, we should have maps based on shared interests of specific geographies throughout the state. This process can be overseen by an independent body that synthesizes information collected by efforts like the PMC. We have enough data to determine maps that would actually help people, especially communities of color, actually be properly represented, but it is a matter of putting that information to work. With the rampant injustices that our communities are facing, we can not afford to wait until the next census to create maps that are just and representative of the people of Wisconsin.

title: WI Needs Competitive Elections
text: Fair elections are crucial to our democracy! We need a system of representation that is responsive to the people, not one that ignores the will of the voters.   Maps should be drawn independently, without partisan interests in mind. Maps should also be drawn to ensure that marginalized communities are represented and able to use their collective voice, rather than have it diluted by being split up into multiple districts.  I urge the Wisconsin legislature to approve maps that achieve these criteria, or for the governor to veto maps that don't meet those requirements.

title: Meggie's Testimony
text: This area has African Americans, middle aged  homeowners with many children. Churches,  Walgreens,  Daycare Centers are important areas. Crime, potholes, resources, affordable housing and healthcare are issues that need attention. If  a community meeting would be held, it would be about Crime, potholes, infrastructure and having a community center.

title: Lisa's Testimony
text: This area consist of Asians, Mexicans, Blacks, Whites. SDC,  Farmers Market, Co-Op are important areas in this community. Washington Park, Washington high school, Library, Affordable housing, SDC are issues that need to be addressed.

title: Town of Forest, St. Croix County, WI
text: The Town of Forest in St. Croix County, Wisconsin, needs to be returned to its historic districts. During the last redistricting, Forest was removed from Assembly 29 and State Senate 10, and placed in Assembly 75 and State Senate 25. Forest has nothing in common with the northern and west central districts. Forest was also the only town in St. Croix County removed and placed in its current district. It is my understanding the last redistricting was done by the Michael Best et. al law firm from Madison, Wisconsin. Coincidentally nor not, Michael Best represented the original wind developer, Emerging Energies Highland Wind project in our Town of Forest. Please see to it that the Forest of Forest is returned to Assembly 29 and Senate 10. Thank you.

title: competitive districts help democracy
text: I believe that gerrymandering is literally STEALING my vote. In the last three state-wide elections the Democrats have gotten around 50% of the vote, but only around 32% of the state legislators.  The other 50% get around 68% of the legislators, so one party has complete control of the legislature, even though they receive about the same number of votes as their opponents. Thus, they can ignore the governors request for special sessions and even ignore considering any of his policies.    He did get more votes than his opponent but becomes almost powerless. Our votes are being stolen.   Fair re-districting would be good for democracy as the best way to win a majority in districts that are evenly divided is to be moderate and willing to compromise. Currently most districts are safe for one party or the other. The primary ends up being the important election. To win the primary you have to cater to those who are further to the left or the right than most people, and when the winners meet in Madison, there is very little common ground to make policy.  The party in power can reward their followers and hurt their opponents. They should be working for the common good.   End gerrymandering.

title: 3rd and 7th CDs
text: I live in Wisconsin Rapids, which is on the far eastern end of a highly gerrymandered district. The 3rd and 7thCD (Congressional District) boundaries run thru Marshfield which makes it very difficult to participate in civic activities that involve voter outreach. It would be so much easier if all of Wood County was in the same CD. I propose adding all of Wood County to the 7th  CD. I think that re-districting should be non-partisan and use county or municipality boundaries whenever possible. I support non-partisan redistricting. I do feel that the current boundaries are unfair and restrict my access to elected officials and make it more difficult for my vote to count.

title: Fair maps are important to me.
text: I live in SouthEast WI.  What happened in WI the last time redistricting maps were drawn is a well known embarrassment for WI residents.  WI is one of the worst gerrymandered States.  And the maps drawn precisely to carve out Democratic communities were done in closed-door sessions led by one side - Republicans.  We cannot let that happen again.  I do not know how to re-draw the maps myself.  But I will be able to recognize an unfair process.   The maps need to be drawn by non-partisan experts.  They MUST be fair representations of the communities and people within them.  I don't know how else to say this.  And we absolutely have to keep special interests and money out of the process.  The maps must be For the People - or they will be against the People.  Please make the redistricting fair and non-partisan.  Make us proud to be residents of Wisconsin again.

title: Fair Maps Are Essential
text: Nothing is more essential to representative government than fair maps  we cannot function effectively without this basic provision in the way we are governed.

title: Fair Maps For the Citizens of WI
text: This week a headline said “GOP Considers Cracking Cities” in a proposed redistricting process. Districts are made up of communities and exploring “cracking cities” is a mockery of that. This lack of ethics is astounding to me. I am deeply disappointed that the Democrat political party did not change the redistricting policy in 2009 when the opportunity arose. In an effort to truly gauge what American’s want, we vote. By gerrymandering our state maps, we don’t get that opportunity because by cracking and packing districts all votes are not weighted equally. For example, we have lax gun laws in WI. Yet most voters when surveyed believe as I do, we need commonsense gun safety. By gerrymandering our maps, we have a minority holding us hostage to a policy most of us consider dangerous. I understand that both parties have been guilty of gerrymandering, so it is time to remove the process from the politicians and return it to the citizens. Fair maps. The time in now.

title: Redraw Wisconsins Maps
text: To whom it may concern,   I frankly find it ridiculous that a majority of Democrats voted blue in 2020, but they only hold 12 out of 33 seats in the state senate assembly. This is not representation. Too many districts in this state are heavily gerrymandered and we are giving more power to a select few within our state. Boundaries need to be redrawn to so that each vote actually matters equally. Otherwise we risk continuing to give more voice to a select few and less of a voice to the majority within this state.   Thank you,  Jake

title: School centered COIs meet all criteria
text: As time presses, we want to save ourselves some work by looking at entities that are already mapped and do not overlap. I feel that centering around schools carries a few advantages: I'm using this link to continue:  *School COIs respect contiguity, compactness and preserve most political boundaries, which are all in the First Order Criteria. * For the Second Order Criteria: With a little sensitivity, because we start with COIs that are small enough [Schools:  There are 5,966 public and Private PK-12 schools in WI but 464 School Districts] it should be possible to spread 5.822 Million residents fairly equally over 99 assembly districts, 33 Senate Districts and 8 congressional Districts. [Those are 2019 numbers. We’ll need to fix that later.] * and we should be able to spread these COIs with less than a 1% deviation so as to respect one person-one vote, which is the Third Order Criteria.  * For the 4th Order, which is Partisan Fairness, I don't really have anything, except perhaps that because we start the work without taking advantage of previous election results, and we will probably have a variety of people drawing maps, not just Rs or Ds but Family Party, People's Party, Workers Party, Green Party, Libertarian, you name it, our work should logically result in a less partisan outcome. * As to the "Additional consideration", which perhaps should be considered as a 5th Order, the competitiveness is also very important to keep our politicians listening, on their toes. I'm not sure how we would go about setting this in the design itself. I suspect our Districts will be more competitive than what we have now, as these were designed with a partisan objective in mind.   As to the actual nuts and bolts of drawing the lines on the map, if we start with Schools, and Districts [464], the work is already done. Our job would then be to group them in a way that respects one person one vote. We will need to explore the map making tool and become more familiar with it.

title: Do not split town's apart
text: My town, Marshfield, is the perfect example of gerrymandering in two ways. First, for our state representative, our small town of 20, 000 is literally split in half. We don’t have a person who can speak for our community’s interests in any sort of way. Second, for state senator our community is also split apart. Even though my address is Marshfield, my state senator is in Chippewa Falls! That is over 60 miles away and she has no idea what the needs and issues are for our area. I never go to Chippewa Falls for anything. If I am not in Marshfield, my shopping, kids' sports, eating out, and any other activities are in Stevens Point or Wausau. Districts need to reflect this.    Anyone with a Marshfield address absolutely should be kept together for both state representative and senator. In the past Stevens Point and Marshfield were always together. This makes the most sense because these two communities are closely tied in several ways such a businesses, medical facilities, and university branches. Plus in the future, I think, these two communities will be even more intertwined and we need representatives who understand this.

title: Impartial Redistricting
text: Our democracy is being threatened by gerrymandering.   Wisconsin needs to have a new system of redistricting that can't be corrupted by politicians, as is the case today.

title: Redistricting by nonpartisan commission
text: Redistricting must be performed by a nonpartisan commission.  NOT LEGISLATORS !  Wisconsin deserves fair maps to be drawn to provide for elections that are actually competitive and mean something.  This will help, over time, bring legislators to a position of compromise rather than the current "my way or the highway" philosophy that is creating extreme divisiveness.

title: Computer Generated Redistricting
text: Like the computer generated concept, but it is unclear what the parameters would be.  I definitely prefer (1) nonpolitical approach,  (2) use of existing county, city, village, township boundaries to the degree possible.

title: Use computer generated redistricting
text: We know that the Census Bureau is delayed in getting the numbers to the redistricting entity this year due to the pandemic.  Why not use a computer generated system to determine the boundaries?  It seems to me it would be a quicker way to redistrict and would meet the timeline for redistricting.  It would also provide the boundaries necessary for the 2022 spring election.  We should put our feet to the fire so that the new redistricting map will reflect the population.  We must also remedy the current atrocious district map.

title: Fair Maps
text: I want our maps to reflect the interests of the voters in my district and not the political motivation of one party over another.   It seems that the majority of the voting population has not been reflected in recent elections.  I do not understand how an election can go to someone else and not the person that got the majority of the votes.

title: AFT-Wisconsin Statement on Fair Maps
text: AFT-Wisconsin stands for Fair Maps. A fair and open redistricting process is free from political interests, fosters public participation, and guarantees every person's vote has equal value.

title: Stop Gerrymandering
text: The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported that Republicans received 45% of votes cast in a recent Wisconsin election for State Senate, but won 55% of the Senate seats. In the same election, Republicans received 48% of the vote for Assembly, but won 57% of Assembly seats. Thus, due to brazen gerrymandering, both houses of the Wisconsin legislature represent only a minority of state voters. When legislative redistricting imposes minority control over the will of a majority of citizens, oligarchy results. Wisconsin's current legislative composition threatens democracy in our state.  The only meaningful solution is to create a nonpartisan commission that will redistrict legislative boundaries, without favor, to ensure that the majority's will is respected. Keep self-interested politicians out of this process.

title: No one's vote should carry more weight
text: One person = one vote. No one should have more influence than others based on where they live.  No political candidate should feel free to disregard the will of the people just because their seat is "safe." Public office holders won't have legitimacy or authority if they are not selected fairly.

title: Non-partisan determination
text: I support the use of completely non-partisian individuals for the drawing of districts for representation of citizens by our elected officials. NO political party should be able to set boundaries to protect themselves in election. Let voters vote based on platforms and have their votes equally mean something. I understand that the constitution requires first the Legislature to handle redistricting, but it does not seem to require the manipulation being done historically by all parties. Wisconsin used to be famous for leading sound and honest government. Let us get back to setting a worthwhile example of how politicians can start caring about ALL Wisconsin citizens again...not just those who vote for them or contribute to their campaign

title: Redistricting Committee
text: I would like a nonpartisan commission established to draw these lines. I do not want either party to do this work. It must be done for the people and not the party!

title: Political Gerrymandering Must End
text: My name is Nichols Troupis and I am a resident of Lake Geneva, WI.   One of the issues that is of paramount importance to me this year is the redrawing of Congressional and Assembly districts. Wisconsin's districts have been some of the most gerrymandered districts in the country for the past 10 years. As evidenced in recent state assembly elections, Wisconsin's population is majority Democratic, yet the majority will has been denied in state government by a form of technocratic manipulation: districts intentionally drawn to give the political minority outsized influence. Republican attorneys have drawn district lines that they know will secure their majority into future election cycles, despite the long-standing Democratic majority.   Wisconsin's population is very unevenly distributed throughout the state; Democratic voters are largely concentrated in Madison and Milwaukee. However, this concentration of Democratic voters, by itself, poses no basis for a denial of the popular will. Several cities, including Madison, have grown at rates higher than the rest of the state in recent years. Wisconsin's population is continually shifting and changing, and many Wisconsinites have found that the opportunities afforded in Dane County surpass many other areas.   This poses a question: Is the state legislature to deny the "one person, one vote" principle to the residents of these "liberal" areas simply because the legislature does not prefer their politics, their culture, or their institutions? No; each citizen of the state of Wisconsin has the constitutional right to have their vote counted in exact proportion to every other citizen of this great state. Whether one lives in Portage or Madison, Lake Geneva or Eau Claire, the people decide for whom to elect not based on crass geography, but from aligning their will with the policies and politics of particular candidates. Any other basis is an abdication of democratic responsibility. If the party in control of the state legislature finds that it cannot attain a government majority through free and fair elections, perhaps it ought to change its policy proposals.  Political gerrymandering is costing the state of Wisconsin, and the nation at large, its civic culture, its competitive elections, and its hopeful optimism for the political future. It's time to end this unsustainable practice.

title: Commission is illegal
text: Only the Wisconsin Legislature  can a create maps.

title: Keep communities together
text: My community, my City, my county should not be divided into multiple districts. My community should not be incorporated into an irregular congressional district that includes obscure areas of central Wisconsin that have different political and social needs than my community. My representatives should be representative of the statewide popular vote and representative races should be competitive.

title: Bipartisan District Committee
text: I do not any All party drawing these districts. I want a committee of bipartisan person's drawing these lines.

title: Support for non-partisan redistricting
text: A non-partisan redistricting group should create fair and equitable maps

title: Districting process must be non-partisan
text: Districting must be a non-partisan process in order to produce a truly representative legislative body of government.  And the truly representative legislative body of government is required for a successful democracy.  Government for the people is the objective, not government for the ruling party.

title: Please stop 🛑 Gerrymandering
text: The people of Wisconsin are so tired of partisan gerrymandering. We don’t have accurate representation at all due to the unfair practice of gerrymandering and it MUST end. Voting Maps must be fair to all if our democracy is going to survive. It’s as simple as that.

title: Lets even the field.
text: Lets set bipartisan and fair district boundaries.  Anything else is underhanded politics.  Are we a legitimate democracy or a farce?

title: Use current county boundaries
text: A redistricting map that has the entire current county boundary in the same district is possible. It does create different looking districts, they would not be the same shape. The only counties that would be broken up would be Milwaukee based on its current population. Other counties around Milwaukee county would probably need to be broken up also. Breaking up of counties should be kept to an ABSOLUTE MINIMUM. Using computers this breakup could keep all 8 districts within the Constitutional 1 %. Attempt to keep racial or poorer neighborhoods together. If something like I-94 or other multi-lane highway already causes a real breakup of the neighborhood use that where possible. The current map should not be considered at all or which party represents a current district should not be considered either. A multi person commission should be created to draw our new map and no current state legislator or current party heads should be on this commission. It is okay to know a persons party preference and the commission should attempt to be as equally represented politically.

title: Why fair maps is important
text: Fair maps through a bipartisan effort makes the most sense. That way I know and so do all the citizens of Wisconsin know that our votes count in every election. NOW is the time to draw fair maps...it shouldn't be that any one party that is in the majority gets to draw the district maps every 10 years. Be fair and allow my opinion and my vote to count, as well as others.   Without fair maps, the votes are being gerrymandered. The election results need to be based on every vote being counted. In many states, the state legislature draws the districts and openly does so in order to influence the likely partisan makeup of the legislature, discourage electoral competition and/or generally hurt their political enemies and help their friends. However, goals like those fly in the face of democratic values like fair representation of voters and the ability of voters to influence election results.   Wisconsin's motto is Forward...make sure we keep moving forward by allowing a bipartisan commission redraw the district maps so we can join the other 13 states that have made the move to include fair maps. There are 72 counties in Wisconsin, 55 of the counties have Proclamations to say they want fair district maps drawn.  I want my opinion known and counted that I am for fair maps.

title: Politicians must not pick their voters.
text: Voters must pick their representatives.  When elected representatives cherry-pick their voters by drawing district maps based on revealed voting patterns, representative government loses it's most important attribute:  it's credibility.  This is clear when we look at popularity polls showing our legislature is generally among the least popular, least respected institutions in our society today.  Districts must be compact, drawn on geographic centroids, and boundaries must be based on logical, defendable, easily explained and commonly reasonable physical features.  Districts must not be based upon economic wealth.  Above all, districts must not be based upon revealed voting patterns.  Because our representation was meant to be based on population, our districts must be based on the numbers of persons, without regard to secondary characteristics of persons such as wealth, race, creed, or any other.  Correctly done, voting districts reduce the well-known inherent advantage of incumbency.  Elections become more competitive.  More people find they can offer themselves as viable candidates. Terms of service will become limited only by the electoral marketplace.  This eliminates the proposed need for government interference in elections by setting arbitrary term limits into statute.  Term limits are a government distortion of the elections marketplace and are a false solution to the problem of incumbency in the same way government price controls are a false solution to goods scarcity.  Let the electoral market become a level playing field and enjoy the benefits of truly representative and much more credible government.

title: Fair & Impartial
text: The commission should do all possible to ensure equal voting power and fair representation.   District boundaries should conform to the existing geographic boundaries of a county, city, or city and county, and shall preserve identifiable communities of interest to the greatest extent possible. A redistricting plan should provide for the most whole counties and the fewest county fragments possible, and the most whole cities and fewest city fragments possible. Communities of interest are defined by similarities in social, cultural, ethnic, and economic interest, school districts, and other formal relationships between municipalities. Political party identification or voting records, race, religion or current Congressional Party holder should not be taken into consideration.  This should be unbiased and not gerrymandered to fit into a political parties strategy to hold onto an office.

title: Portage County
text: Portage County should remain in the third congressional district. If not the third then the sixth or the eighth congressional district or even split if possible ex. (Wisconsin River or I-39,U.S 51 and or I S 10) as this is good for procurement of federal and state  funds and grants. Portage County is a small metropolitan county and that Portage County has far more in common issues with the third, sixth and the eighth congressional districts then we ever had with the "up north" seventh congressional district. Also that by changing the districts is a good thing as it has constituents doing their homework and not just an automatic in as it was prior to 2011. To my knowledge in these parts of Wisconsin, it's pretty damn hard to have gerrymandering transpire in this part of the state.

title: Fairness all around
text: The redistricting process needs to be made as fair as possible, even if that means the political party I align myself will be hurt in the process.  It is the constituents who choose their representation, not the other way around.  The redistricting process should also be made as transparent as humanly possible so that no malfeasance can take place.  Without these changes, the democracy we cherish will slowly erode into nothing and we will be a shell of the country we once were.

title: There Is No Democracy with Gerrymanderin

title: Nonpartisan election maps important
text: There is no way that parties that will directly benefit from the redistricting should be designing the maps.  Gerrymandering has happened as a result of Republicans in Wisconsin, Democrats in Illinois, and it is not fair to the voters.  If our elected officials want to provide an example to other states on true democracy, let the voters pick their officials - not the other way around.

title: A Step For The People
text: Part of the American Anti-Corruption Act is to prevent and reverse Gerrymandered maps that allow our politicians to choose their voters. This is a broken part of our system. We the People are supposed to choose who represents us - but by allowing these maps to be drawn by the politicians we have invited corruption into our government. It is an unavoidable consequence and unacceptable. This practice establishes and embeds unfair political advantages, it dilutes the power of voters; that is AMERICANS whose voice must be heard. This is one step in several that must be fixed state-by-state. Let's follow our fellow states that understand the need for citizens to once again have a powerful voice and fix our districting maps.

title: Algorithm to determine districts
text: Rather than having a commission meet every 10 years I would like to see a statute pass that defines an algorithm to set district bounties every 10 years.   This would prevent either party or incumbents from drawing maps that protect their interests.  As populations shift the algorithm will automatically shift and districts won't be gerrymandered in ridiculous ways.  As an example, divide the state population by the number of districts, then starting in the southeast corner go north X amount of census districts, proceed west X census districts until a line connecting the north and south borders is within X% of the calculated average district size.  Census blocks split by the north and south running line would be in out based on whether 50% or more of the geographical area is in the block.  This would complete the first district and then you would complete the process by proceeding west until you hit the western border of the state, at that point you go up the same amount of census blocks on the western border and proceed east.  Obviously it would take more fleshing out but leaving it to a formula takes the bias out of setting the districts.  It would be impossible to know how populations and political leanings will shift so it would eliminate the gaming of gerrymandering by both parties.

title: Milwaukee-area river watersheds
text: The Milwaukee area is part of five river watersheds and areas that drain directly to Lake Michigan. (A watershed is the area of land that drains to a body of water.) This COI submission approximates the five major river watersheds (Milwaukee River, Menomonee River, Kinnickinnic River, Oak Creek, and Root River, with direct drainage areas not highlighted). The Milwaukee, Menomonee, and Kinnickinnic river watersheds comprise the Milwaukee River basin watershed, the area important for consideration by a unique multi-municipality TMDL water quality agreement. The stormwater and runoff from these three watersheds all contribute to water quality in the Milwaukee Estuary, designated one of the Great Lakes' Areas of Concern by the federal EPA. The western edge of these watersheds also constitute the Great Lakes Basin (subcontinental) divide, a hydrological boundary important to the multi-state Great Lakes Compact agreement, with the Root River planned to receive return flow from the City of Waukesha under its approved diversion request for Lake Michigan water to be supplied via Milwaukee Water Works. To the extent that political district boundaries can respect or conform to watershed or subwatershed boundaries, the more closely we can expect to collectively align policy, identity, and activity to support clean water and manage water resources.
area_text: This COI unscientifically approximates the Kinnickinnic River watershed, Wisconsin's most densely populated river watershed. A watershed is an area of land that drains into a body of water. In this case, the KK River and its tributaries, many of which are highly channelized but which MMSD and partners are retrofitting for flood management and community benefits. To the extent that political boundaries can harmonize with human/natural system boundaries like our watersheds, more focused political and cultural activities to protect and preserve our waters and waterways are likely. For more accurate geofiles, consult WDNR or USGS. Also note: Kinnickinnic River watershed is part of the Milwaukee River Basin watershed which is the area important for the multi-municipality TMDL agreement.

To the extent that political boundaries can harmonize with human/natural system boundaries like our watersheds, more focused political and cultural activities to protect and preserve our waters and waterways are likely. For more accurate geofiles, consult WDNR or USGS.

title: Milwaukee North Shore - Cheryl
text: I think of my community as being the North Shore of Milwaukee - within Milwaukee County. I believe that the inner ring suburbs have a distinctive identity and shared values:  high quality public education, high quality public services, the importance of preserving our natural environment - both Lake Michigan and all concerns about water quality, watershed preservation, erosion, and the importance of green space and its associated concerns - toxic runoff, green space as a public good. Another tie that binds is the belief in the importance of the health of the City of Milwaukee, and the willingness to contribute to the tax base of Milwaukee County. We value the city and quality of public services, and we are willing to pay for them. This is why Ozaukee County should NOT be included in electoral districts with parts of Milwaukee County. While we share some values and concerns with our neighbors to the North, we are willing to pay for the urban infrastructure that supports the entire community. Ozaukee (and other WOW county) residents have fled the taxes and refuse to support the amenities that they also enjoy.

title: Jefferson/Dane Healthcare Delivery
text: The State of Wisconsin has been divided in Health Emergency Response Consortiums (HERCs) that reflect citizens' actual patterns of healthcare delivery, especially at the emergency level. Jefferson and Dane Counties are part of the South Central HERC, reflecting the fact that they share  significant common patterns in healthcare delivery. Convenience is a large factor in where people receive their healthcare. Convenience is also a large factor in where people educate their children  and also do their shopping.  They are de facto a community of interest.

text: Small Rural North Central Wisconsin County

title: Energy and Flooding in S. Driftless
text: This COI looks at flooding areas long the driftless, also energy issues in rural S. Drifteless Region
area_text:
> Community concerns around energy distribution in rural areas including broadband, ATC power lines
> Community access to communications -- an issue because of limited companies that offer broadband. There is a dependency on these businesses -- which are not offering sufficient services.  Utilities decide where to offer business not the demands of the community. "FCC Reverse auctioning" process is granting utilities with the least investment ownership over sections of the rural census blocks. (The community was not consulted) During the time of this grant other utilities cannot compete to provide service to these areas. Current solutions (towers) don't work due to the geography. Fiber-optics are needed. Community needs control over providers. Schools are also suffering from insufficient services - which were highlighted by COVID-19 and the need for virtual teaching. 
> Rural access to economic and technological opportunities are limited by wifi/broadband connection -- this is affecting the sale of homes, and economic value of some properties. This is also affecting the ability of small business/and farms (which are prevalent in the area) from growing/thriving/maintaining business. 
> Large portion of the constituency is interested in renewable energy production
area_name: Broadband/Energy Issues in Southern Driftless Region

title: Milwaukee Neighborhoods - Three Make One
text: Milwaukee’s Central City, Three MAKES ONE Three makes one is my community of interest. It is three distinct neighborhoods in Milwaukee’s north east side: Riverwest, Harambee and Brewers Hill. The area is bounded by the Milwaukee River on the east, Light industry on the north, I43 on the west and Walnut Street on the South.   The housing stock is mostly small working class duplexes and single family structures built in the early 1900s. Larger, fancier homes are located in the southern end. The original residents were of Polish and German descent followed by African and Hispanic Americans. Proximity to UW-Milwaukee has brought a vibrant youth and artistic flair to the eastern part of this community.    This cultural and racial diversity creates a special and unique place for people to live, work and socialize together. Because of this diversity our community forms a strong multicultural and generational voice that must remain whole within the new election districts being drawn this year.   Currently, our community is divided into three Assembly districts despite being a tight, well defined area within Milwaukee. This divides us when the whole-of-us have so much to offer our community, city and state. The unity in our diversity is captured in the name of one of our neighborhoods Harambee, a Swahili word meaning “let’s pull together.”   Keep us whole. Keep us together in single election districts. Thank you.
area_text:
Is a diverse community including white and African -American residents and also Hispanic. The the  housing stock is included both small working class cottages plus larger single family and duplex houses. 

Also there is a large artist community and several cooperatives including a bar, food and specialty beer operations.

area_text: this part of Door County is more cosmopolitan that southern Door. It is the main tourist area and the area reflects more diverse interests. title: Jefferson County Fair Maps/Palmyra-Eagle
text: This map was created by the Jefferson County Fair Maps Coalition from interviews with residents in the Palmyra area.
area_text:
For all of reasons listed in the communities described here, this Palmyra-Eagle Area COI should not be split during future redistricting activities.

The village communities of Palmyra and Eagle in this community of interest are traditionally closely linked despite being separated by the Jefferson/Waukesha County Border. They both share one school district. Both are located near the heart of the southern unit of the Kettle Moraine State Forest which has more than 20,000 acres of glacial hills, kettles, lakes, prairie restoration sites, pine woods and hardwood forests. The Palmyra Community of interest is situated at the extreme upper end of the Scuppernong River and lies about fifty miles from both Milwaukee and Madison. However, most general shopping trips extend no further than the 20 miles to Waukesha or 40 miles to Janesville. Eagle was founded in the 1830s, having previously been part of Mukwonago, and even earlier, it was part of Genesee. Palmyra was a later addition to the area in 1866. From 1870 to the early 1920’s, people from across the country visited Palmyra enjoying the healing waters at the Palmyra Spring Sanitarium on Blue Spring Lake, which is just outside of Palmyra Village Borders. Now, Blue Spring Lake is known for its water ski team, which includes area kids from as far as Mukwonago.  In the late 1950’s the building was razed and the land leveled, but this era helped shape the history of Palmyra.

There is robust local industry in the Palmyra COI, but people commute for work to larger surrounding communities like Waukesha, Janesville and even Madison. The Fort Atkinson Memorial Hospital is a principal provider for people’s health care in the Palmyra COI.

title: Jefferson County Fair Maps/Palmyra-Eagle
text: This map was created by the Jefferson County Fair Maps Coalition from interviews with residents in the Palmyra area.
area_text: There are a number of establishments in Palmyra that are frequent gathering spots for local residents all year long.  The Turner Museum and McKenzie/Carlin Historical House at the corner of Third and Main Street in Palmyra are popular tourist sites.   A number of clubs, like the snowmobile club, meet in several restaurants along the main street of Palmyra.  The T&D Bar and Restaurant on Main Street for example attracts local groups regularly. Palmyra has a very active library and recreation department. For example, the Powers Memorial Library in Palmyra holds a very popular ‘End of Summer’ reading festival which includes the local band. The Palmyra Community Center and Recreation Department are also heavily utilized gathering spots featuring many activities for people of all ages in the Palmyra COI.  For outdoor community activities, the Palmyra local parks are very popular.  Palmyra has a twelve-acre park facility for example, equipped with a pavilion for group gatherings and, a playground that includes, tennis, basketball and volleyball courts. In the summer, Palmyra Beach on Lower Spring Lake is very busy. Palmyra Industrial Park provides many jobs for the area.

title: Jefferson County Fair Maps/Palmyra-Eagle
text: This map was created by the Jefferson County Fair Maps Coalition from interviews with residents in the Palmyra area.
area_text: Eagle is best known for its central location in Southern Kettle Moraine and for Old World Wisconsin, a "living museum" with a collection of traditional buildings moved from sites all around Wisconsin. Eagle also has a very active library and recreation department. The Eagle Community Center is a heavily utilized gathering spot featuring many activities for people of all ages.

title: Jefferson County Fair Maps/Palmyra-Eagle
text: This map was created by the Jefferson County Fair Maps Coalition from interviews with residents in the Palmyra area.
area_text: The Palmyra-Eagle Area School District has two elementary schools, one in Palmyra and another elementary school in Eagle. There is a combined Palmyra-Eagle Middle/High School in Palmyra.  The district supports a wide range of youth and family activities on a year round basis. Recently, more students in Eagle are traveling to Mukwanago rather than Palmyra, which has generated some local controversy within the school district.

title: Jefferson County Fair Maps/Palmyra-Eagle
text: This map was created by the Jefferson County Fair Maps Coalition from interviews with residents in the Palmyra area.
area_text: Kettle Moraine State Forest extends from northeast of the Palmyra-Eagle COI, then through the COI, and then southwest of the COI. Being within the Kettle Moraine State Forest, the Palmyra-Eagle COI has many tourists and recreationally oriented groups frequenting the area.  Surrounding the Palmyra COI are some of the best hiking, mountain biking and Nordic skiing trails in the Midwest, including a 30-mile segment of the acclaimed Ice Age National Scenic Trail. Bicycle touring routes and snowmobile trails lead right into town and miles of equestrian trails, plus a state forest campground just for horse riders, are at Palmyra’s doorstep.  The Palmyra Lions Club holds a fishing clinic to give people of any age the opportunity to enjoy the sport of fishing.  In contrast to forests and waterways, some of the most productive agricultural land in Wisconsin is located just northwest of Palmyra in the Scuppernong Valley.  In the summer, fields of carrots, onions, potatoes, corn and other produce stretch for miles.
area_name: Kettle Moraine State Forest - Southern Unit

title: Fitchburg and Related Communities
text: The city of Fitchburg closely borders Madison, Oregon, and Verona.  I believe Fitchburg has or will annex the Town of Madison as well, but I am not sure of its boundaries.  Fitchburg does not have its own school district so it's very important for it to have its own city identity (and not to be split in half or into portions).   In addition, depending on where you live in Fitchburg, you might be in one of three school districts:  Madison, Verona, or Oregon. Thus, when drawing state or federal district lines, it makes more sense for Fitchburg to be on its own or with cities with which it shares school districts.  Furthermore, my Fitchburg residence is in the Verona Area School District and while the school district includes Verona it also includes parts of Fitchburg and parts of Madison.  So, there often is a blending of these four communities:  Fitchburg, Verona, Madison, and Oregon.

title: Central Wisconsin Education Community
text: Due to recent reorganization of the University of Wisconsin system – The University of Wisconsin Stevens Point is now responsible for managing and administrating not only their own campus, but those in addition in both Wausau and Marshfield. Due to strategic partisan redistricting, Stevens Point is no longer in the same congressional district as these two other campuses. They have been split away. Another example of the devious technique of “cracking” of perceived communities which include progressive and moderate voting residents. This situation demands a rational remedy. All of these educational communities of interest serving many diverse regional residents need to be in the same congressional district. Period.

We opened the theatre in 1974 and closed our doors in 2019.

title: Oregon School District
text: The Village of Oregon is conveniently located  about 7 miles south of Madison on Hwy 14. Many of the people who live in the Village commute to Madison for employment.  The Village is attractive for its location, excellent school system, small town atmosphere and beautiful parks. The Oregon School District includes 4 elementary, 1 intermediate, 1 middle and 1 high school. In 2017, the OSD Student Population Growth Task Force analyzed the capacity of existing schools and the predicted student population growth within the OSD area and determined that another elementary and middle school would be needed within 10 years. Since then, an elementary school (one of four) was built in the northern part of the district. A new middle school is on the horizon in the next few years.  OSD is highly regarded in Dane County for its academic, sports, and arts programs.   The Village of Brooklyn is located about 3 miles south of Oregon and is part of the Oregon School District. There are few employers in Brooklyn, and most residents commute to work. Commercial development in Brooklyn has been slow, although there have been repeated efforts to attract businesses to the industrial park on the east side of the Village.

title: DeForest Area COI using sch dist
text: Since the DeForest Area School District is a reasonably compact area including the Villages of DeForest and Windsor and the Town of Vienna (all of which also share use of the DeForest Area Community and Senior Center and the DeForest Area Public Library), it seemed logical that this would provide a basis for a Community of Interest for discussion.
area_text:
The Village of DeForest is a growing community located just ten minutes north of Madison.  DeForest is dedicated to ensuring a premier municipality for roughly 10,619 residents (2019 est) through its beautiful park system, safe neighborhoods, and quality public services. 

The 2019 estimated population of 10, 619 represents almost a 20% increase over its 2010 census population.

title: DeForest Area COI using sch dist
text: Since the DeForest Area School District is a reasonably compact area including the Villages of DeForest and Windsor and the Town of Vienna (all of which also share use of the DeForest Area Community and Senior Center and the DeForest Area Public Library), it seemed logical that this would provide a basis for a Community of Interest for discussion.
area_text:
The DeForest Area School District (DASD) has 3 elementary, 1 intermediate , 1 middle and 1 high school. It serves the Village of DeForest, most of the Village of  Windsor, parts of the towns of Vienna, Bristol, Burke, Leeds, and Hampden, and parts of the Cities of Madison and Sun Prairie. 

There are approximately 3,850 students.

The nine-member Board of Education is elected based on geographic districts, with three members each elected from DeForest and Windsor, one from Burke, one from the combined towns of Burke and Leeds, and one from the District at large.

title: DeForest Area COI using sch dist
text: Since the DeForest Area School District is a reasonably compact area including the Villages of DeForest and Windsor and the Town of Vienna (all of which also share use of the DeForest Area Community and Senior Center and the DeForest Area Public Library), it seemed logical that this would provide a basis for a Community of Interest for discussion.
area_text:
Windsor is a village and former town in Dane County, Wisconsin. The population was 6,308 at the 2010 census. and is  estimated at 7,644 for 2019, an increase of 21%. 2020 Census results are not yet available. The communities of Lake Windsor, Morrisonville, and Token Creek are located within the village. 

Windsor voted to incorporate as a village on November 3, 2015; prior to its incorporation, it was a town, and a portion of the town was a census-designated place. Windsor is a part of the Census Bureau's Madison metropolitan statistical area.

A portion of the former town was part of a disputed annexation by the Village of DeForest. In July 2004 the village and town reached a settlement in which part of the disputed area would be annexed by DeForest and part would remain with Windsor. In addition, the town and village agreed to exchange other less populated land.

Under Wisconsin State law, Town land is vulnerable to annexation by adjacent Cities and Villages. This is one of the primary reasons that Windsor sought to incorporate as a Village and include its entire town area within its Village boundary.

title: DeForest Area COI using sch dist
text: Since the DeForest Area School District is a reasonably compact area including the Villages of DeForest and Windsor and the Town of Vienna (all of which also share use of the DeForest Area Community and Senior Center and the DeForest Area Public Library), it seemed logical that this would provide a basis for a Community of Interest for discussion.
area_text:
Vienna is a mostly rural town between the villages of DeForest and Waunakee. Its children are split between the DeForest, Waunakee, and the Lodi School District.

Its 2019 estimated population of 1,575 represented a bit more than a 6% increase over the 2010 census.

title: Appleton School Dist. + City of Appleton
text: This map includes 95% of voters within the Appleton Area School District. area_text:
> broadband access across rural Wisconsin: Coops provide best broadband access, some of the surrounding geographies (hilly areas) that aren't serviced by the coops are not getting any broadband. Other utilities aren't willing to work with very small communities/populations. Utilities are claiming broader coverage than is accurate. Coops are not able to go into these rural or sm. population areas to support. 
> There is no city and water sewage in Buffalo City. Each home has its own septic system from the 60s that are outdated and often in need of repair -- is probably affecting the river as well. It would be very very expensive for City of Buffalo residents to pay for city sewage. Biggest city in Wisconsin that doesn't have its own sewage system. 
> Townships being together is important 
> Roads and bridges are very important to this (Driftless) region.

text: common areas of shared interest along the Mississippi and along the north ends of the counties are different
area_text:
> Buffalo and Trempealeau Counties really gravitate toward the City of LaCrosse, Winona for employment, shopping, recreation, medical care and education including vocational schools. 
> These counties have much more in common with folks south towards La Crosse (along HWY 35) , as well as folks East - West along HWY 10. Often instead they are grouped with Eau Claire -- which makes sense for small towns such as Mondovi (which has commonalities with Durand/Pepin Co.) -but not towns such as Buffalo City and townships south of there.

title: NorthShore Milwaukee County Communities
text: The municipalities between the City of Milwaukee and the Ozaukee County line are a shared community of interest.  Together, they form the inner suburbs of Milwaukee to the North Side.  While this set of communities are suburban in nature, they share an interest in the adjacent City of Milwaukee, in which many North Shore residents work and enjoy various cultural activities.  Shorewood, Whitefish Bay, and Brown Deer each have their own school district, and the remaining communities are in the Nicolet school district.    Lake Michigan, the Lake Michigan Shoreline, the Milwaukee River, and Estabrook  Park are all points of interest.

title: Markets, metros, economic social COI
text: This plan focuses on media markets and Census defined statistical areas to form the basis of 21 distinct regions that should be basic guidelines for districting at the State and Federal levels. Most regions are larger than state Legislative Districts although many are the approximate populations of an ideal set. Only one region, the Milwaukee MSA, is larger than a Congressional seat, coming in at about 2, for 1.575M people.  These districts should be put together to form Congressional districts and divided to form Assembly seats. Of course, nothing will perfectly divide into the correct numbers of seats so we can form some districts by crossing into other regions but we should try to use others that have some common characteristics like Media Market.    I chose Media Market as the initial dividing line criteria because they see a common set of local news and have many common points of reference. I would argue that even though fewer people now watch traditional TV stations, these local news COIs are even more relevant due to the decline of local print media.  TV markets define a lot of the background of contemporary culture from everything including what sports teams we pull for (Bucks/Timberwolves, Packers/Vikings) as well as so many economic factors in our life. Typically, they align major health and education institutions as well as turf for retail outlets and distribution.  From there, it's Metropolitan Statistical areas, and counties that determine much of our COIs. Within highly populated regions, County and municipal boundaries should set up the next criteria to determine districts. This is particularly so in the Milwaukee MSA, which requires 2 Congressional seats and nearly 9 State Senate and 27 Assembly seats! But also, these boundaries should for the basis of districts drawn in the GB/Appleton, Madison, Racine/Kenosha,  MKE exurban, and Wausau regions for Senate seats. Tre rest of the regions are about the size of a single Senate district or smaller so the main issue will be finding appropriate borders for Assembly Seats to build out 99 distinct COIs statewide.
area_text: Milwaukee Census designated Metropolitan Statistical Area (MKE market 1)

title: Vivian's Oregon Map
text: The Village of Oregon is lovely with a growing diverse population. There is a high voter turnout in the Village and level of civic engagement.  People are proud to live in Oregon. The older part of the Village is turning over with younger families moving in. There are senior living facilities here. Affordable housing is an issue.  There is strong political group here.
